<solution>
<p>Please email the <ref uri="mailto:team@doenet.org">Doenet team</ref> with a link to this problem and we will reply with the solution.</p>
  
<!-- <p>There are <m>171</m> solutions.</p>
<p>One way to attack the problem is to choose a value of <m>z</m> and see how many pairs <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> can go with it.  For example, if <m>z = 1</m> then <m>x + y = 19</m> and so there are <m>18</m> such <m>(x, y)</m>  pairs (since <m>x</m> can be anything from <m>1</m> to <m>18</m>).</p>
  
<p>If you look at this carefully, you see that if <m>z</m> is any number from <m>1</m> to <m>18</m> there
are <m>(19 - z)</m> pairs <m>(x, y)</m> that can go with it.</p> 

<p>This means our answer is <m>1 + 2 + \dots + 18</m>. The trick to getting this sum is to write the equation forward <m>S = 1 + 2 + \dots + 18</m> and then backward <m>S = 18 + 17 + \dots + 1</m> and, adding the numbers in the same position obtain <m>2S = 19 + 19 + \dots + 19</m> so <m>2S = 18 \times 19</m> and so <m>S = 9 \times 19 = 171</m></p>  -->
</solution>

